{"/service/ndnp/mimtptc/batch_mimtptc_inkster_ver01/data/sn88063294/00340589075/1945082301/0685.xml":{"full_text":"How Far Can He Go Alone?\nBp: r '\"?\u00a3TTs*'*\nPav Off at Home\n\n(CONSIDERATION for our fighting\nmen should not end with their\ndischarge from the armed forces.\nIt should follow and protect them\nALL THE WAY HOME.\nToo many discharged service\nmen, paid off at separation centers\nin great cities far from their homes,\nhave fallen victim to robbers or\nswindlers and finally arrived home\npenniless and dispirited.\nThat is a poor homecoming for a\nman who has fought his country\u2019s\nbattles.\nIt transforms an occasion that\nshould be one of pure joy both for\nthe returning soldier and for his\nfamily into one of chagrin for the\nman and perhaps of anxiety both for\nhim and for the family.\nMost discharged servicemen need\ntheir final pay to start them off in\ncivilian life, and most of them, being\nwell able to take care of themselves,\narrive safely home with it.\nBut those who do NOT arrive\nEmployment Will Come\n'THE war bubble has burst, as we\nall knew and prayed\u2014that it\nwould.\nThat it has hit Detroit hard\u2014\nprobably harder than any one area in\nthe country was expected. We\ncould not be the Arsenal of Democ\nracy, the makers of the greatest\narray of weapons ever unleashed\nagainst a foe, without experiencing\nthis result.\nNo one expected, or wanted, this\nvast war economy to continue, no\nmore than any one ever expected\nWillow Run to turn out bombers for\never. We had a job to do and we did\nit. The results we attained justify\nany price we may now pay.\n\n'THE price we are to pay now is\nunemployment. That, too, was to\nbe expected. We could not build up\nthe great arms industry here to turn\nout planes, tanks, guns, trucks,\nweapons, munitions\u2014yes, even parts\nfor the atomic bombs\u2014without at the\nsame time building up a vast force\nwhich we did not expect to absorb in\nits entirety when peace came.\nOur jobless total has been swelled\ndouble in the past week. It is still\ngrowing and for a while, it will con\ntinue to grow.\n\nT>UT the situation is neither shock\ning nor hopeless. It calls for\nTEST By Sabina 4'onnallv\nI\u2014Australia is called: The\nLand Down Under; <b) The\nI .and Over Yonder; (c) The\nLand There Over.\nU\u2014At whose deathbed did some*\n4ne vay. \"Now he long- to\ninra\u00dfes\"\u2019 a Franklin;\nLincoln; (ei JefTet>on\n8-C\nTHE DETROIT TIMES\nAe*. 1945\nhome with their pay must experience\nthe tragedy of facing the immediate\nfuture with empty pockets, and that\nis a tragedy from which they should\nbe saved if possible.\nIn almost every case they COULD\nbe spared this bitter experience if\nthey received their final pay IN\nTHEIR HOME TOWNS AND\nNEIGHBORHOODS, rather than in\ncities far from home.\nWhy should they not be sent\nHOME before they are paid off, and\nwhy should not the task of giving\nthem their separation pay be handled\nby the local draft boards that started\nmost of them on their way to mili\ntary service?\nThat would not be difficult to ar\nrange, and it would insure that al\nmost every soldier would arrive home\nwith his pay in his pockets.\nIt would avert, for many service\nmen and their families, the sadness\nof a spoiled homecoming and the\nprivations attendant upon trying to\nstart a new life without money.\nneither cries of despair nor predic\ntions of doom. It is an understand\nable state of affairs that a few short\nmonths can change.\nGive this great city and its great\nindustries time to shift gears and\nchange over to its peacetime work,\nand unemployment, will fade aa\nsurely as shadows before the rays of\nthe sun. Once the machines of death\nare exchanged for the tools that pro\nduce a greater abundance for life,\nDetroit will again become the dy\nnamic city it has always been.\n\nr pHE temporary displacement in\nthe factories is just that, as the\nTimes has attempted to point out in\nits news columns. Under the leader\nship of such industrialists as Knud\nsen, Wilson, Keller, the Fords and\nthe rest, we can have faith unemploy\nment will not be permitted one\nminute longer than can be avoided.\nAhead of Detroit lies an era that\ncan only be called golden. The mar\nkets for our products are waiting\neagerly. The same \u201cknow-how\u201d that\nstood us in such good stead during\nthe war will bring us back to the\ncrest of prosperity that has been our\ngood fortune these many years.\nHave faith in the destiny of our\nnation and Detroit, in peace as well\nas in war.\n3- In \"Uncle Tom\u2019s Cabin\u201d the\nKiri that crossed the ice with\nbloodhounds chasing her was:\n\u25a0ai Topsy; tb) Ophelia; (c)\nEliza.\n1 The famous British\nnuisc in World War I was:\n\u2022a* Sarah Hale; \u00bbb> Edith\n'Cavell; (c> Margot Asquith.\n3 The most romantic real In\ndian girl in Amanca was:\n(a) Pocahontas; (b) Minne\nhaha; (c) Ramona.\n6-Match these columns cor\nrectly; they go together:\nia bleacher money\n<b\u2018 ni.ii.leaner t\u00abr i evrnlni cwl\ni< bleedlnt-heart smn atajnd at\nid \u00ab\u00bballii\u00bb-tat: t>4\u00abehall game\n1 i \u00bbhlffle-ue\u00ab (jri bar so which\n\u2022he liacea of hai\nmii are fattened\n4a i flower\n\\n\u00abwrr\u00bb an Oppe\u00bbit\u00ab Page)\nPaul\nMallo\\\n\u2014Behind\nThe News\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 22\u2014The\ndrive of the senders to\nstampede Congress with depres\nsion pressure publicity is not\nmaking much headway yet.\nA couple of rather influential\nadministration senators have\ntalked around among their col\nleagues and reached two con\nclusions, (1) congress is apt to\nbe tighter than before about\nmoney, and (2) the govern\nment just simply cannot provide\nevery one with a job, or the job\nhe wants at the pay he wants.\nMayor LaGuardia flailed the\nmicrophone the other day, for\ninstance, with some cyclonic\ncontentions that we are heading\nfor a terriflc unemployment, de\npression and what not from\ncancellation of War contracts,\nunless congress immediately\ndoes something\u2014and he knew\nwhat had to be done, specifying\nmore appropriations for bigger\npublic works,.including $1,250.-\n000,000 of them in his own\npocket.\n\nTHE outside information from\nthe financial district in the\nsame newspapers a few pages\naway from LaGuardia gave not\nthe slightest hint of depression.\nPeople who had their money,\nincluding life savings in stocks,\nwere not selling them. Prices\nwere not depressed, although\nthe owners had heard the line\noffered by LaGuardia, not only\nfor weeks, but all during the\nlatter years of the war.\nLaGuardia further claimed\n\u201cCongress has done nothing,\u201d a\nclaim any congressman can ex\nplode to full ridiculousness by\nadding up the $27,200,000,000 in\nthe spending\u2019 program already\nauthorized mainly by them (see\nyesterday\u2019s column), a total\nthree times the height of the\nRoosevelt free spending pro\ngrams, when the federal debt\nwas a small fraction of the\n$265,000,000,000 it was at the\nclose of the war.\nThe wilting Little Flower,\nwho apparently is generating\nsome hopes for personal but\nnot a patriotic national revival\nalso admonished citizens not to\nspend their money\u2014and thus\nfurnish jobs\u2014but to keep their\nbonds and buy as little as pos\nsible. This seems to be a de\nfeatest policy generated by mo\ntives beyond my imagination or\nability to reason.\nThat kind of advice would\nforce people out of jobs and\ncreate unemployment.\nTo do that would scuttle the\neconomic equilibrium of the\ncountry.\nIs LaGuardia so eager for\nmore federal money that he\nwants a drepression to get it?\n\nIF THERE is to be unemploy\nment, LaGuardia should be\nrequired to say where is all\nthat money collected from the\npeople*in New\u2019 York through the\nsales tax for the specific purpose\nof unemployment compensation\n\u2014collected all during the war\nwhen labor scarcities prevailed.\n(State unemployment, com\npensation funds are now $6,000,-\n000,000.)\nUnless they can organize a\npolitical movement to sweep\nCongress off its feet and make\nit forget what it knows about\nwhat it has done, and blind\nitself to the facts and figures\nbeing published, and get the\nstock market to collapse, there\nwill be a strong fight over\nspending with the outcome in\ngrave doubt.\n\nSENATORS Wagner and Mur\nray, (who arc not the two\nunidentified senators quoted at\nthe outset, but generally work\ning along the CIO road with\nLaGuardia) came out of a\nWhite House conference saying\nMr. Truman favored their bill\nto give every man a government\njob if he does not find another\none (cost unestimated) and\nboost the unemployment com\npensation.\nHowever, other senators say\nprivately Mr. Truman inherited\nthis program from Mr. Roose\nvelt and thought he should go\nalong with it.\nThey noted that so far he has\nnot however joined the La-\nGuardia CIO depression stam\npede.\nConsequently it may be wise\nto await developments.\nLuatrthufyd by Kin* i-faturea By nd.. Inc\nReproduction In whole or In part\n\u2022trlrtly prohibited.\n\u25a0train (panto\nI\u2014Eor what feat do people re\nmember Steve Brodie?\n2 Art chimerical things: (a)\namusing; (b) imaginary; (c)\nugly?\n3\u2014How w'ere the Allied armies\nfighting in Europe supplied\nwith the large quantities of\ngasoline required in modern\nwarfare?\n4 \u2014What president of the U. S.\nwas a university football\ncoaeh in his younger days:\nWilliam Howard Taft, Wood\nrow Wilson or Teddy Roose\nvelt\n5 True or false: (a) Cancer is\nsaid to cause more deaths\nthan so-called heart disease;\n(h) The Ist, 2d, 3d and 4th\nair forces have been sta\ntioned in continental U. S. as\na protection,against air at\ntack.\n6 John Hodiak plays the lead\nin the movie version of \"A\nBell for Adano.\u201d Who pl\u00dfys\nthe same part in the Broad\nway play?\n7 What is the name of the\nJapanese army base on w hich\nthe first of the new atomic\nbombs was dropped?\nS\u2014What is a quahog?\nHearst Papers Thanked\nFor Youth Movement Aid\nWINONA LAKE CHRISTIAN\nASSEMBLY, INC.\nWinona Lake, Ind.,\nAur. 6. 1945.\nMR. WILLIAM RANDOLPH HEARST,\nSAN SIMEON, CALIF.\nMY DEAR MR. HEARST:\nMAY I, in behalf of the Winona Lake\nChristian Assembly, as its executive\nmanager, express our sincere thanks and\nappreciation for the attitude you\nas well as the space you are requesting your\npapers throughout the country to give to this\ngreat Youth for Christ movement.\nWe believe it is the remedy for child de\nlinquency and, if given the proper publicity\nand co-operation of the press along with such\nmen as Dr. Torrey Johnson of Chicago as\npresident, as well as the group of men he\nhas with him, it will, we believe, change the\nwhole course in life for millions of young\npeople.\nWe had one of the greatest gatherings of\nthis type ever held at Winona Lake last week.\nThere were tremendous crowds. The music\nand speaking were outstanding and we be\nlieve this movement took a tremendous leap\nforward.\nA great deal of the success was due to\nthe publicity and co-operation given by your\npapers and may I express my personal and\nsincere gratitude for the wonderful work done\nby one of your reporters from the Chicago\npaper, Mr. Wesley Hartzell. He is a splendid\nyoung man and did a great piece of work here\nfor us. He was most co-operative and seemed\nto sense immediately what, was real news\nvalue and what should be printed to give the\nbest information for this great work.\nAgain thanking you for your co-operation\nand interest, I remain, very truly yours,\nARTHUR W. McKEE.\n\nMOODY MONTHLY\nChicago, 111.,\nAug. 7, 1945.\nMR. WILLIAM RANDOLPH HEARST,\nHEARST RANCH,\nSAN LUIS OBISCO COUNTY', CALIF.\nDEAR *R. HEARST:\nTHERE is no use trying to make you recall\nhaving met the writer. Out- of the mul\ntiplied thousands you meet and hear from,\nyou could not be expected to remember more\nthan a handful.\nBut this will serve as an introduction\nSome years ago, when I was pastor of the\nBaptist Tabernacle, Atlanta, Ga., the ad\nministration of Oglethorpe University asked\nif they might borrow our great auditorium\nfor their commencement, at which you were\nto be given an LL.D. I was made chaplain\nof the occasoin.\nI have noticed with real interest and deep\nsatisfaction what you are doing through your\nnewspapers for the \u201cYouth for Christ\u201d move\nment. Steadily the Chicago Herald-American\nhas given valuable space to the encourage\nment of this cause.\nRecently I visited Los Angeles, and your\npaper in that city was giving the same kind of\nbacking. Evidently this is under your direct\ninstructions.\nAll right-thinking Americans must be dis\nturbed by the indications of a morals letdown\nfor this generation. There is not only the\nproblem of juvenile delinquency, but the evi\ndence of flabby morals on the part of many\nyoung parents, and all through that age\nbracket.\nI believe the \u201cYouth for Christ\u201d move-\nGeo. Koto well Brown\nr FHE two billion-dollar atomic\nbombs which brought Japan\nin cringing surrender to the\ngood neighbor she bad treach\nerously attacked at Pearl\nHarbor, could be the only tw-o\nbombs of this cosmic power ever\nto be dropped on this earth.\nThey may be the first, the\nonly, and the last atomic weap\nons ever to be used for the\npurposes of war, and they can\nenjoy this distinction if the\nUnited States, having this ter\nrible secret in its possession,\nlocks up in complete security\nfrom all the world, including\nour closest allies.\nThere is already a powerful\nopinion in high circles in Wash\nington that this secret should be\nkept as a secret of the United\nStates alone, to be used in the\nfuture by this country alone as\na guarantee of perpetual peace.\nThe question as to what au\nthority in this government shall\nmake the decision is already in\nthe minds of members of the\nlegislative branch. Congress\nmay by legislation declare that\nthe executive side of the gov\nernment, now in possession of\nthe secret,^shall not divulge it\nto any other country.\n\nr FIIE proposal has already been\nmade that the secret of the\nsplitting of the uranium atom,\nand the patents covering the in\nvention of the method for con\nfining this power within a bomb,\nshould be transferred, as a sort\nof sacred trust, to the council\nof the United Nations, as\ntrustees.\nThat would make it as secret\nas a piece of news that has been\nbroadcast over every radio\nhookup in the world.\nScientists here are by no\nmeans unanimously of the\nopinion that this fateful secret,\nfor the good or ill of mankind,\ncannot be kept so far as its\napplication to war is concerned.\nScience has known how to\nsplit the atom, but the manu\nfacture of the bomb inyolVes\npatent* which can be kept\nsecret. The question also arise*\nment has a real contribution to make in\ncleansing the minds and raising the standards\nof this very important generation.\nPermit me, sir, to thank you and com\nmend your papers on this fine, unselfish con\ntribution to a good cause. As a token of\nappreciation, and to further help \u201cYouth for\nChrist,\" I am going to use this letter to you\nas an editorial in the Moody Monthly.\nSincerely yours,\nWILL H. HOUGHTON,\nEditor..\n\nWASHINGTON COUNTY (PA.)\n\u201cYOUTH FOR CHRIST\u201d\nCharleroi, Pa.,\nJuly 18, 1945,\nMR. WILLIAM RANDOLPH HEARST,\nTHE PITTSBURGH SUN-TELEGRAPH,\nPITTSBURGH, PA.\nMY DEAR SIR:\nTHE youth of today are potentially the\nleaders of tomorrow. The kind of a world\nin which they shall live depends largely upon\nthe kind of a challenge given them by today\u2019s\nleaders.\nYou, sir, are to be congratulated for your\nkeen interest in this matter as evidenced in\nyour sincere willingness to bring before the\npublic the activities of \u201cYouth for Christ.\u201d\nAs a publisher, you have done well to chal\nlenge the good thinking of your readers. As\na man, you have ably done your best to inform\nAmerica of great impending dangers awaiting\nits youth.\nYoung people are going to hell every day\nbecause nobody offers them any other place\nto go! Youth delinquency is growing by leaps\nand bounds the world over! America, already\nvictorious in Europe and hopeful of victory\nin the Pacfic can still be brought to her knees\nthrough her folly! God will not be mocked!\nPowers and principalities are nothing to Him\nand yet He blesses the humble, faithful, be\nlieving individual.\nThe \u201cYouth for Christ\u201d movement is striv\ning to bring the youth of our land to a better\nknowledge of God\u2019s plan for man.\nWe are winning \u201cteen-age\u201d fellows and\ngirls every day to a cleaner and better way\nof life.\nWe are helping to bring the youth back\nto the church.\nWe are holding the ministry of His w-ord\nhigh and we are backing the office of our\nclergymen which is God ordained.\nWe humbly thank you for your interest.\nRespectfully,\nDAVID A. RECONNU,\nDirector.\n\nKENOSHA-RACINE \u201cYOUTH FOR CHRIST\u201d\nKenosha, Wis.,\nJuly 16, 1945.\nMR. WILLIAM RANDOLPH HEARST,\nSAN SIMEON, CALIF.\nDEAR MR. HEARST:\nON BEHALF of Kenosha-Racine \u201cYouth\nfor Christ\u201d we wish to tender our sin\ncere appreciation for the publicity given to\n\u201cYouth for Christ International,\u201d and Kenosha-\nRacine \u201cYouth for Christ\u201d in particular, by\nthe Milwaukee Sentinel, and other Hearst\npapers throughout the nation.\nYour co-operation in this matter is cer\ntainly appreciated, and proper credit will be\ngiven publicly for your co-operation.\nSincerely,\nC. J. ANDERSON,\nDirector, Yonth for Christ.\nof the control by the victors in\nWorld War II of all the avail\nable supplies of the essential\nraw materials.\nThe atomic bomb has un\ndoubtedly injected a .actor into\nthe question of preserving the\npeace of the world that rendered\nthe San Francisco charter obso\nlete before the ink had fairly\ndried in the American signa\ntures which ratified it.\n\nIVTIIAT effect the appearance\nin the world of this dead\nliest of weapons of war will\nhave upon the acceptance of the\ncharter by those nations which\nhave not yet ratified it Is of\ncourse problematical at this\ntime.\nBut that the whole ques\ntion of world peace w-ill have\nto be re-examined in the light\nof a bomb which draws its\nLetter to Mr. Hearst\nMR. WILLIAM RANDOLPH HEARST,\nSan Simeon, California.\nMy Dear Mr. Hearst:\nlAM one of the millions of inarticulate Americans who\nseldom make expression, either favorable or adverse,\nof what they read in the newspapers.\nI want, however, to express my very deep apprecia\ntion of the very excellent statement in last Sunday\u2019s\nissue of the Chicago Herald-American entitled \u201cHalf\nMillion Youngsters Leading America Back to Faith\nin God.\u201d\nTo my way of thinking, this fair land of ours is in\ndire need of faith in God, and it is very heartening to see\na large and influential newspaper giving prominent place\nto that which contributes to national righteousness and\nusefulness.\nPlease accept my very sincere appreciation for the\nexcellent work done by the Chicago Herald-American in\nthis task worth while.\nWith every best wish, I am very truly yours,\nV. R. EDMAN,\nPresident, Wheaton College.\nPolitical\nParade\nenergy from the same forces\nwhich created and control the\nuniverse, and the countless uni\nverses beyond our own univerie,\nought to go without saying.\nNot merely the military dis\narmament of Germany and\nJapan, but the most rigid super\nvinon of laboratory research by\nthem, must be enforced to pre\nvent a future war of revenge\nthat might annihilate mankind\nand destroy the planet in the\nprocess.\nThe surest insurance against\nthis would be the knowledge of\nthe world that the United\nStates alone possessed the\nNClft, that it possess, rj and\ncontinued 1o possess the actual\nweapon itself, and that it would\nuse that weapon mercilessly at\nthe first appearance anywhere\nof a will to conquer the world\nby force.\nWestbrook\nPegler\n\u2014Fair\nEnough\nIT SAYS here that the treasury\nis going to give a report to\nthe House ways and means com\nmittee on the 28th of the month\nabout Elliott Roosevelt\u2019s loans\nand, of course, that will be ai\ngain, although it seems that\u00ae\nthey might have saved labor if\nthey had waited to do the whole\njob in one batch and send it\nover in a truck.\nBut I have been wondering\nwhether they plan to touch up\nthe Charlie Harwood matter\nbecause the official blow-off In\nthe House occurred back in\nJune and concerned only the\nJohn Hartford bite for $200,000,\nwhereas Harwood didn\u2019t open up\nuntil the twentieth of July.\nJust to familiarize you,\nCharlie Harwood is a New York\nlawyer and a nice, docile old\nparty plug who often tossed a\nfew mibfi on the blanket for\ncampaign purposes and had\nideas about a spot on the U. S.\nDistrict Court or the court of\nappeals or one of those special\ncourts where a fellow can work\nin his undershirt on hot days\nand nobody the wiser, because\ntit is covered up with that black\nkimono, but wound up m one of\nthe meanest jobs, at President\nRoosevelt\u2019s command, under the\norneriest boss in the whole gov\nernment.\n\nMR. BIG got him to be con\ntent for a while with the\ntitle of governor of the Virgin\nIslands which meant that he\nhad to work for Harold Ickes.\nHarwood's rtory is that he\nloaned $25,000 to Elliott\u2019s Texas\nradio network in March. 1939,\nwhen he certainly was honing\nfor some job.\n\nCHARLIE wants you to believe\nthat Elliott never talked\nloan to him, although the fello\\J|\nwho first told me about it. mo: H\nthan a year ago, was fresh from\ntalking with Charlie and said he\nwas singing blue for his $25,000\nand related that Elliott did see\nhim and that they together\ncalled up the president and that\nhe thanked Harwood for stand\ning the touch.\nHe says nope, however, that\nwasn't the way tt was, hut that\nHall Roosevelt, Elliott's uncle,\ngave him the come-on for quite\na spell with stories about the\nwonderful prosr>ect.s of the net\nwork and. finally, sunk home the\nbook in March. 1939. telling him\nthat at last his chance had come\nto catch 250 shares by lending\nthe company 25m.\nWell, where I think Harwood\nmade his mistake was in depict\ning himself, a candidate for the\nfederal bench, and a pretty\nsmart and successful lawyer, as\nthe lender in a deal with a cor\nporation where no officer of the\ncorporation appeared in the ne\ngotiations and not even an I. O.\nU. was given nor any terms were\nput in writing.\nThat doesn\u2019t sound true to me\nhut it is his story and he is\nstuck with it.\nThen, as a fellow will when he\nfs trying to move off a spot,\nCharlie puts it that this was to\nhe a two-year loan with the\nstock for collateral, and never\ntheless. in 1942. after the stock\nwas supposed to be his by de\nfault. to have and to hold and\nall like that, he wrote to the\ncompany asking how about It?\nAnd the company said to set\ntle it with Elliott, who. as you\nwill bear in mind, to hear\nCharlie tell it, had had nothing\nto do with the deal whatever.\n\nI DIDN\u2019T know for sure bi^l\nsome pretty good lawyer*\nhave told me a company can\u2019t\ndo that way. borrowing scratch\non the nod and taking some\nshares out of the safe for se\ncurity and then saying to go see\nGus about it\nThese lawyers sav you have\nto make some writing on a piece\nof paper and sign names to it\nhut. then, as I say. old Charlie\nknows a spot law 1 himself, and\nyet that Is his way of how- they\nwent anrf done.\nI guess I forgot to mention\nthat he was gr*\u00bbd enough for\nPresident Roosevelt to appoint\nto the U. s. District Court for a\nshort trick down in Panama, so\nI guess, anyway, he can read ft\nchattel mortgage or a lease.\nAnd Ihen. finally, how can\nyou get away from the part\nwhere Joe Hartfield, another\nNew York Demo and a lawyer\nwho does Jesse Jones\u2019 business\nfor him, goes to Charlie Har\nwood and steers him to Jesse,\nwho had picked up the Hartford\nstuff for 2 cents on the dollar,\nto talk about settling this one\nfor 5., W or |1,000\u201d to help\nw-ash the slate? What for was\nthe secretary of rommerre and\n\u2666he chairman of the RFC mess\ning around in the debts of a\ncorporation, if this was a com\npany loan, and suggesting that\nCharlie might as well chunk it\nin and take a tax loss?\nCharlie didn\u2019t do It. He\nfigured he might as well lose It\nall if he had to and he thinks\nthe value has bounced back, al\nthough, like a dope, here I have\nbeen sitting all this time with\nout finding out just what It i*\nW'orth today.\nElliott\u2019s lawyer is Randolph\nPaul, a heavy duty ideologist\nwho used to be general counsel\nfor the treasury and of course\nhe still has some pals there.\nBut it certainly would be fun\nto hear them straighten this one\nout, considering that, according\nto Harwood\u2019s dates, he put up\nhis dough and then got the joo\nas governor of the Virgin\nIslands.\nCop/rlght. 1*49. br King ffalum","height":"27846","width":"21495"}}
